WEBVTT

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:13.470
In 1998,
Apple Computer became the first computer

00:00:13.470 --> 00:00:18.000
company to make open source development
part of its ongoing software strategy.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:21.970
We've had great successes then,
and today we'd like to give you an update

00:00:22.050 --> 00:00:26.200
and status on some of the projects,
which includes Darwin itself,

00:00:26.200 --> 00:00:30.000
QuickTime Streaming Server,
OpenPlay/NetSprocket.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.780
At this point,
I'd like to bring on stage the

00:00:32.780 --> 00:00:35.790
director of CoreOS Engineering,
Brett Halle.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:45.440
Good morning.

00:00:45.440 --> 00:00:48.370
Certainly open source at Apple,
I think one should realize,

00:00:48.370 --> 00:00:52.000
is becoming fairly pervasive
through our project plans.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.110
And certainly this isn't the only session
at all that's dealing with open source.

00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:58.000
But in this session,
we're going to spend some time

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.230
today and actually go over kind
of more of the infrastructure and

00:01:02.230 --> 00:01:06.000
mechanisms and stuff behind what
we're doing around open source.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.630
And you can learn a lot about
open source throughout the week

00:01:08.630 --> 00:01:10.000
and other sessions as well.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.000
There's a huge number of
technical sessions for Darwin,

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.100
something on the order
of 20 different sessions,

00:01:14.100 --> 00:01:16.000
as well as some of the
other technologies.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
So it's not just here we're going
to be talking about open source.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.210
This is something that's pretty
consistent throughout much of

00:01:23.270 --> 00:01:25.000
the technology discussions.

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:28.750
So we're going to spend a few minutes
and talk about a number of the various

00:01:28.750 --> 00:01:31.000
projects around open source at Apple.

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:32.790
In addition,
we're going to give you a little

00:01:32.790 --> 00:01:35.050
idea of where we're going,
particularly in some of

00:01:35.050 --> 00:01:36.000
the infrastructure and
stuff that we're doing.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.120
We're going to talk about how we're
going to support to kind of enable open

00:01:39.130 --> 00:01:40.960
source development in the community.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.050
And most importantly,
how you can get involved and

00:01:44.050 --> 00:01:46.000
participate in the process.

00:01:46.950 --> 00:01:51.400
So first, it's worth mentioning that
our public source license,

00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:55.210
version 1.2,
was released just a little while ago.

00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:57.760
And that's actually been
extremely well received.

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:00.270
Since the original release
of our public source license,

00:02:00.270 --> 00:02:02.800
we've been working with the
community to kind of refine it

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:07.800
and make it work well for both
our developers and Apple Computer.

00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:09.770
And I think we've done extremely well.

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:14.350
And clearly the community believes that
because we've been approved by the OSI as

00:02:14.350 --> 00:02:16.800
being a certified open source license.

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:23.590
Certainly something
we're very happy about.

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:27.330
I'd like to now actually make
a bit of an announcement that

00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:32.120
we've added a new project to the
open source projects at Apple.

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:37.300
This is CDSA,
the Common Data Security Architecture.

00:02:37.620 --> 00:02:38.940
Thank you.

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:43.100
Sounds like that one person
is very excited about this.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:45.320
This is an open group standard.

00:02:45.490 --> 00:02:49.130
It's basically the basis,
the underlying foundation for a lot of

00:02:49.130 --> 00:02:51.420
the security features within Mac OS X.

00:02:51.690 --> 00:02:55.890
Support for the key chain and
other key services of the system.

00:02:56.010 --> 00:02:58.760
It provides a number of modular
plug-ins for cryptography and

00:02:58.760 --> 00:03:01.890
certificate management and key
management and things like that.

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:05.900
This is now available as of today,
I believe.

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:08.740
We got all the stuff all up
last night and this morning.

00:03:08.850 --> 00:03:14.740
It should be available now on our website
for you to download and play with.

00:03:14.700 --> 00:05:43.800
[Transcript missing]

00:05:43.990 --> 00:05:47.010
There's a ton of projects
being ported to Mac OS X,

00:05:47.010 --> 00:05:50.460
and I think to a large degree that's
because of the open source nature of

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:52.600
Darwin and other parts of the system.

00:05:52.670 --> 00:05:57.470
It really fosters the philosophy of
being able to get these kinds of services

00:05:57.470 --> 00:05:59.700
and capabilities under the system.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.950
As of today, for example,
as I understand it,

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:09.990
on sale in Developer Depot is a
CD of something like 1,200 ports,

00:06:09.990 --> 00:06:12.830
BSD ports from the ports collection.

00:06:12.900 --> 00:06:14.080
1,000?

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:14.840
2,000!

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:15.840
Oh my goodness, sorry.

00:06:15.950 --> 00:06:19.820
You know,
tools and commands and applications,

00:06:19.830 --> 00:06:23.890
if you will,
to run into the Darwin environment.

00:06:24.970 --> 00:06:51.470
and David LeRoy.

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:52.730
Also, I think that's one of the other
aspects that we think is pretty

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:52.730
important is being able to actually
keep up with the community at large.

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:52.730
There's an order of magnitude more people
involved in the development process and

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:52.730
there's a way to really leverage that
community far beyond the walls of Apple.

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:52.730
I think it's a pretty important
capability and facility.

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:52.730
Certainly,
all of this really comes down to

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:52.730
trying to make sure that we make the
best possible products we can for

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:52.730
our customers and our developers.

00:06:52.900 --> 00:08:33.000
[Transcript missing]

00:08:33.210 --> 00:08:36.460
and much like there's
quality benefits for us,

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:39.340
I think that's true as well to
the open source environment.

00:08:39.370 --> 00:08:42.930
The reason it works is because
there's a lot of people working

00:08:42.930 --> 00:08:46.590
on the technologies and everybody
benefits by the improvements in the

00:08:46.670 --> 00:08:49.730
quality and testing capabilities.

00:08:49.860 --> 00:08:52.620
For Apple, this community is growing
pretty significantly.

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:57.430
Since we released Darwin,
we've had over 700,000 downloads,

00:08:57.430 --> 00:09:01.060
which is pretty darn significant.

00:09:01.220 --> 00:09:05.480
Even the next door is clapping,
I think this is great.

00:09:05.510 --> 00:09:08.130
They think it's pretty cool.

00:09:08.130 --> 00:09:13.460
We've had over 95,000 users
registered on our site.

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:18.030
And that's a pretty significant
developer community.

00:09:18.030 --> 00:09:24.390
Our mailing list activity year over year
has grown by two and a half times a year,

00:09:24.390 --> 00:09:25.900
it's exponential.

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:25.900
And we're at this point about 1,800,
you know,

00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:29.840
items in the mailing list
discussions every month,

00:09:29.910 --> 00:09:32.620
and we see this growing at
a pretty ferocious rate.

00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:36.220
Clearly as we've reached major
milestones of reaching to the developer

00:09:36.220 --> 00:09:40.600
preview releases and the public beta
and now of course the final release,

00:09:40.630 --> 00:09:43.890
this ends up being pretty
significant milestones of

00:09:43.890 --> 00:09:46.320
developer involvement and adoption.

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:51.000
And as people continue to port their
products and technologies to Mac OS X,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.710
this is a great forum for
them to participate in.

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:56.900
If you're not on the mailing list,
we encourage you to.

00:09:56.900 --> 00:09:59.010
There's a lot of great discussion there.

00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:03.700
There's a lot of activity going on,
specific activity going

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:05.870
on in the community well.

00:10:05.870 --> 00:10:10.400
Certainly we're actively involved
in supporting the FreeBSD and

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:12.770
changes and things that we have.

00:10:12.770 --> 00:10:15.140
There's a very vibrant
relationship there,

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:20.320
sharing information about security issues
and collaborations that we're doing on

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:22.960
packaging and other kinds of things.

00:10:23.020 --> 00:10:23.930
Also, we work very tightly
with the IT department.

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:24.460
We're very involved in the
development of the freeBSD.

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:24.460
We're very involved in the
development of the freeBSD.

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:25.650
We're very involved in the Apache group.

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:31.090
We've certainly had them on campus and
sponsored their activities and try and

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:36.420
provide hardware and other things to them
as well as fixes to support the platform.

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:41.220
The X386 project, MySQL, PAM, et cetera,
there's a number of projects where

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:44.050
there's been a lot of two-way activity.

00:10:44.300 --> 00:10:48.170
In addition,
there's been quite a lot of interest in

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:53.240
the open source developer community to
actually port Darwin to the X86 platform.

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:56.000
And we've, you know,
been supporting that work.

00:10:56.090 --> 00:10:58.240
That's not something that, you know,
we're doing for any

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:00.140
product direct interest.

00:11:00.140 --> 00:11:02.740
This is something the community
is pretty excited about doing.

00:11:02.740 --> 00:11:06.040
And as that work continues to evolve,
we take the fixes and changes

00:11:06.120 --> 00:11:10.620
incorporated in the source base so that
people can take advantage of one shared

00:11:11.010 --> 00:11:13.720
source for all of that technology.

00:11:13.740 --> 00:11:16.470
The streaming server has been ported
to just about every significant

00:11:16.530 --> 00:11:17.890
platform that's out there.

00:11:17.900 --> 00:11:20.730
And as a result,
you can make sure that it's

00:11:20.730 --> 00:11:24.880
possible that you can stream
QuickTime content on just any,

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:26.900
anything that you want.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:31.080
Also, certainly I'm sure you've seen
recent announcements on things,

00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:35.840
new participants in
NetSprocket and OpenPlay.

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:37.800
And there's been a lot of
positive progress there.

00:11:37.800 --> 00:11:40.220
And we'll talk more about
that in a few minutes.

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:43.400
In addition, we've been really, you know,
working with the community.

00:11:43.400 --> 00:11:46.500
As I said, there's been a lot of fixes
and things that have come in,

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:49.470
things like security fixes or
other fixes that have come in.

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:51.560
We've actually, you know,
watched those things.

00:11:51.650 --> 00:11:54.420
If there are opportunity,
we fold them into software updates.

00:11:54.420 --> 00:11:58.120
So as you have seen, we've had, you know,
three software updates

00:11:58.120 --> 00:11:59.620
since Mac OS X was released.

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:01.840
And in those,
when there's been opportunities

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:04.970
to include security fixes or
things from the community,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:05.880
we do.

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:08.910
And like I said already,
the support line has been kind of now

00:12:08.920 --> 00:12:12.070
kind of dealing with this new concept
of getting fixes along with their,

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:12.980
with bug reports.

00:12:13.060 --> 00:12:17.400
So there's been quite a lot
of exciting activity there.

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:21.790
We have this as part of the
infrastructure for working

00:12:21.900 --> 00:12:24.000
with the open source community.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:25.680
As I mentioned, it's not just Apple.

00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:29.510
We actually have people in the
community who actually have write

00:12:29.510 --> 00:12:33.920
access to our CVS repositories and
actually in a position to contribute

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:38.520
directly to the code for Darwin and
some of these other projects.

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:41.220
And these folks we
call Darwin Developers.

00:12:41.220 --> 00:12:44.800
These are partners in the open
source arena for a number of

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:47.120
specific open source projects.

00:12:47.120 --> 00:12:51.720
They should be considered peers to
the rest of the engineers and people

00:12:51.720 --> 00:12:56.140
at Apple in terms of their ability
to help contribute code changes

00:12:56.140 --> 00:13:00.080
and kind of participate in the
process of evolving the source code.

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:03.470
They can help with questions and then
certainly they're in a position because

00:13:03.470 --> 00:13:08.380
they have CVS commit access to be able
to commit changes and modifications

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:11.360
and things into the CVS repositories.

00:13:11.360 --> 00:13:13.670
Obviously from a standpoint of
just managing the source code,

00:13:13.750 --> 00:13:14.860
it's not a very easy thing to do.

00:13:14.860 --> 00:13:16.480
But again,
we do try and make sure that they

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:19.930
are specific point people for
each of the key technologies.

00:13:19.940 --> 00:13:22.360
But again, it's worth noting that those
people aren't necessarily

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:26.240
people who work for or at Apple.

00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:29.970
These developers are folks
that the community and the

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:35.400
core team of Darwin have
selected for technical ability,

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:39.390
kind of well-known participation
in the open source community,

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:43.830
folks that are actually approved
by the Apple executive management.

00:13:43.890 --> 00:13:48.330
So that they actually -- we are giving
them access to our repositories,

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:49.340
like I said.

00:13:49.410 --> 00:13:51.600
There's quite a number of
people who are involved in this.

00:13:52.960 --> 00:13:59.110
and here's a list of some of the
key people if you're involved with.

00:13:59.470 --> 00:14:02.400
And one important announcement
that I want to make today is that

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:09.900
we've just recently in the past day
signed Jordan Hubbard of FreeBSD to

00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:15.360
be part of the Darwin core team.

00:14:15.910 --> 00:14:20.070
Jordan, if you can raise your hand.

00:14:20.070 --> 00:14:22.000
If you know,
Jordan is actually one of the

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.180
founders of FreeBSD and is certainly,
I think, the real spiritual leader

00:14:27.180 --> 00:14:29.900
of the FreeBSD community,
if you will.

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:34.380
We really take involvement and
collaboration with that community

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:37.900
to be a very serious goal of
Darwin and our open source project.

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:41.900
So we're really glad to have
him on as a Darwin developer.

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:44.530
In addition, there's a large number
of other people here.

00:14:44.600 --> 00:14:45.900
I won't go through this.

00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:46.900
You can look at the list.

00:14:46.910 --> 00:14:48.980
But you'll actually get a chance
to meet some of these folks here a

00:14:49.170 --> 00:14:51.670
little bit later in the presentation.

00:14:52.570 --> 00:14:57.100
So from my particular section of this,
I think one other thing to note, again,

00:14:57.100 --> 00:15:01.030
is that there's some really important
benefits we see to open source.

00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:03.460
This is not an experiment for us.

00:15:03.590 --> 00:15:08.540
This is the way we do business for
Mac OS X and for a large number of our,

00:15:08.580 --> 00:15:09.860
you know, technologies.

00:15:09.950 --> 00:15:12.770
And this is something that we're
really working to try and make

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:14.360
work well for Apple Computer.

00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:16.810
We really, you know,
think this is something that we're,

00:15:16.870 --> 00:15:18.340
you know, is a real benefit to you.

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:21.190
We think it's a benefit to Apple,
to the open source community,

00:15:21.190 --> 00:15:22.300
and to our customers.

00:15:22.430 --> 00:15:24.700
And we really would like to, you know,
have you guys be part

00:15:24.700 --> 00:15:25.740
of that more and more.

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:29.200
So if you get an opportunity,
please get on the mailing list,

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:30.750
get involved,
and we'll talk a little bit more

00:15:30.750 --> 00:15:34.660
about how you can do that and some of
the specifics in just a few minutes.

00:15:35.120 --> 00:15:39.620
You'll see, as mentioned today,
with the growth of addition of

00:15:39.640 --> 00:15:42.670
CDSA now in our open source arsenal,
that, you know,

00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:46.190
this is something that we're, you know,
continuing to evolve and grow

00:15:46.190 --> 00:15:50.540
projects that we think are appropriate
candidates for open sourcing at Apple.

00:15:50.620 --> 00:15:52.100
And, you know,
if you're interested in it,

00:15:52.100 --> 00:15:54.820
if you think you're one of those
people who really can make a

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:58.740
contribution and want to be directly
involved as a Darwin developer or

00:15:58.740 --> 00:16:03.850
just as part of the Darwin community,
we'd love to have you.

00:16:03.950 --> 00:16:06.610
So up next in the presentation,
we have a number of things

00:16:06.670 --> 00:16:07.390
we're going to talk about.

00:16:07.530 --> 00:16:10.810
Dave Dozicki is going to come up next
and talk about some of the support

00:16:10.810 --> 00:16:15.100
resources and kind of the mechanisms
for supporting the community.

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:17.480
He's also going to talk about
Darwin itself and how you

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:20.120
can get involved in building
and working with that.

00:16:20.230 --> 00:16:21.900
Chris LaCroix will talk a bit
about the streaming community.

00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:23.760
He's going to talk about
the streaming server.

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:26.560
Lane Roth for NetSprockets and OpenPlay.

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:30.260
And Ron Hayden will talk about our open
documentation efforts with HeaderDoc.

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:32.660
And we'll also do some Q&A in the end.

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:35.600
And on that, I'll pass this on to Dave.

