It makes things a little
bit tough to figure out.

00:31:32.150 --> 00:31:33.840
We are working to correct that.

00:31:33.840 --> 00:31:37.310
We will combine both of those
projects into a single project

00:31:37.420 --> 00:31:39.040
that will be called OpenPlay.

00:31:39.040 --> 00:31:42.300
This will alleviate some of the
weirdness with having multiple

00:31:42.300 --> 00:31:46.910
directories that are the same name
and some duplication of source files,

00:31:46.910 --> 00:31:47.830
so forth like

00:31:48.110 --> 00:31:53.300
The current NetSprocket source is
available and will remain as such,

00:31:53.390 --> 00:31:59.680
but all future work will be on
the combined OpenPlay project.

00:32:00.920 --> 00:32:04.570
Okay,
so the networking API is designed to be

00:32:04.570 --> 00:32:10.020
cross-platform and protocol agnostic.

00:32:10.020 --> 00:32:12.280
Currently,
it is running under Mac OS X in

00:32:12.280 --> 00:32:17.900
a carbonized form under
Mac OS as well as under Windows.

00:32:17.900 --> 00:32:23.490
There is a TCP/IP network module that
is available for all of those platforms,

00:32:23.560 --> 00:32:26.900
and then Apple Talk is
available for Mac OS.

00:32:27.200 --> 00:32:30.760
There are three API layers
to the new OpenPlay.

00:32:30.880 --> 00:32:35.030
There's the game interface,
and that's the highest level interface,

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:37.870
which was known
previously as NetSprocket.

00:32:37.900 --> 00:32:42.890
That interface is what most of the
games and other applications will use.

00:32:42.900 --> 00:32:47.890
The protocol interface was the
former straight OpenPlay interface.

00:32:47.900 --> 00:32:52.060
It's a lower level interface
just for connecting and

00:32:52.060 --> 00:32:54.900
passing packets back and forth.

00:32:54.900 --> 00:32:59.190
The networking interface is
just a wrapper to go around

00:32:59.190 --> 00:33:04.900
the different networking APIs,
and most people won't be using that.

00:33:06.150 --> 00:33:09.130
It all comes together as you see.

00:33:09.230 --> 00:33:15.150
Your application can talk to any one
of the three APIs within OpenPlay.

00:33:15.430 --> 00:33:23.990
You can also talk directly to any of the
OS networking APIs as you feel needed.

00:33:23.990 --> 00:33:26.200
Inside of OpenPlay,
the game interface talks to the

00:33:26.310 --> 00:33:31.420
protocol interface and that talks
to the net module interface that is

00:33:31.420 --> 00:33:35.920
selected for whichever game you're
running and it will talk directly

00:33:36.090 --> 00:33:40.350
to the networking API in the OS.

00:33:42.330 --> 00:33:45.700
Okay, so the game interface, as I said,
is the highest level interface.

00:33:45.820 --> 00:33:49.600
This is basically the NetSprocket API.

00:33:49.690 --> 00:33:53.440
It's the easiest way for
you to add functionality,

00:33:53.440 --> 00:33:56.500
networking functionality to your game.

00:33:56.600 --> 00:34:00.750
The APIs handle hosting games,
joining games,

00:34:00.750 --> 00:34:06.050
it handles all the game management,
it handles your player management

00:34:06.560 --> 00:34:09.400
for just two or more players.

00:34:09.470 --> 00:34:13.100
It also handles packet management,
so you can send data back

00:34:13.100 --> 00:34:14.700
and forth very simply.

00:34:14.700 --> 00:34:20.830
You don't have to worry about a lot
of the details like all the wrapper

00:34:21.170 --> 00:34:27.400
functions are in the cross platform
segment are swapped in their byte order.

00:34:27.490 --> 00:34:32.040
You still are responsible for
doing that for your specific data,

00:34:32.180 --> 00:34:36.340
but you don't have to worry
about all the underlying data.

00:34:36.430 --> 00:34:39.100
That's all handled by those APIs.

00:34:39.180 --> 00:34:44.400
It's cross platform again, OS X, Mac OS,
Windows.

00:34:44.800 --> 00:34:48.330
The protocol interface is
a lower level interface.

00:34:48.330 --> 00:34:56.690
This is where all the platform
agnostic and networking wrappers are.

00:34:56.760 --> 00:35:00.850
Like I said,
there's IP for all the platforms

00:35:01.370 --> 00:35:04.270
and there is Apple Talk for Mac OS.

00:35:04.460 --> 00:35:10.900
And then besides running
on the mentioned platforms,

00:35:10.900 --> 00:35:17.150
this interface has a start
into a Linux version and that

00:35:17.150 --> 00:35:19.770
is underway by the community.

00:35:21.600 --> 00:35:25.580
The networking interface is just
a very low level wrapper to go

00:35:25.580 --> 00:35:27.600
around your different protocols.

00:35:27.690 --> 00:35:32.140
It has a plug-in design so that
in the future if it's needed,

00:35:32.250 --> 00:35:37.220
somebody can drop in a new protocol
module and they can do that

00:35:37.630 --> 00:35:40.030
independent of the release package.

00:35:40.070 --> 00:35:44.180
So you can do it just if you
have some private networking

00:35:44.180 --> 00:35:48.750
API that you need to do,
you can have your own separate module

00:35:48.770 --> 00:35:51.190
and not have to check it into CVS.

00:35:51.980 --> 00:35:56.820
This single API can also be used
by your program if you want to have

00:35:57.280 --> 00:36:02.900
that very low level control and
still have the network diversity.

00:36:02.900 --> 00:36:06.900
And that's it.

