00:36:19.350 --> 00:36:22.330
So a couple years ago,
Apple obviously did a big leap into

00:36:22.630 --> 00:36:26.650
open source with Darwin and then a few
months ago we did another major leap

00:36:26.730 --> 00:36:29.100
into open source with our documentation.

00:36:29.100 --> 00:36:35.890
It was a recognition that
the documentation is often as

00:36:35.890 --> 00:36:35.890
important as the source code and

00:36:39.150 --> 00:36:44.210
What the purpose of this project is,
is to provide the tools and

00:36:44.210 --> 00:36:48.640
resources to allow developers to
provide the documentation directly.

00:36:48.970 --> 00:36:50.160
Which is very exciting for me.

00:36:50.230 --> 00:36:53.530
I've worked for a long time in
technical publications and one of

00:36:53.730 --> 00:36:57.460
the things I've discovered is that
frequently the writers are a bottleneck

00:36:57.520 --> 00:36:59.100
to the information that you need.

00:36:59.100 --> 00:37:02.470
The engineer may have the information,
especially reference material.

00:37:02.550 --> 00:37:06.100
The engineer may have written down
that information for the writer.

00:37:06.100 --> 00:37:09.100
The technical support people
may have the information.

00:37:09.100 --> 00:37:13.100
Some of our customers using the
product may have the information.

00:37:13.250 --> 00:37:16.100
But because of the enormous number
of things the writers have to cover,

00:37:16.100 --> 00:37:18.100
that may not get into the next release.

00:37:18.100 --> 00:37:19.100
And it's wrong.

00:37:19.100 --> 00:37:20.060
And it's a problem.

00:37:20.100 --> 00:37:25.220
So one of the things that we're learning
from open source is how to remove that

00:37:25.220 --> 00:37:29.000
bottleneck and let the person who has
the information provide the information

00:37:29.130 --> 00:37:31.100
as quickly as possible to the audience.

00:37:31.100 --> 00:37:34.560
This doesn't mean that we're not writing
documentation anymore or that we're

00:37:34.560 --> 00:37:36.100
asking the community to provide it all.

00:37:36.100 --> 00:37:39.520
We have a Darwin Technologies writing
team which is concentrating on

00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:41.100
some of the big picture stuff.

00:37:41.100 --> 00:37:43.470
So we're doing an
IOCAP fundamentals book,

00:37:43.520 --> 00:37:47.380
we're doing KEX tutorials,
we're doing stuff on handling

00:37:47.490 --> 00:37:49.100
USB and HID and such.

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:51.870
But the actual reference material
is more and more frequently

00:37:51.870 --> 00:37:55.100
coming directly from the engineer
and getting into people's hands.

00:37:55.100 --> 00:38:00.100
So here's the things that we cover
in the Darwin Documentation Project.

00:38:00.140 --> 00:38:04.000
First and probably most
